{"entity": "Regulation (EU) 2016/679", "type": "content", "description": "Regulation (EU) 2016/679, commonly known as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), is a regulation of the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union. It serves as a comprehensive Union data protection law designed to safeguard the fundamental right to the protection of personal data and privacy. The regulation governs the processing of personal data, mandating transparency and specific governance practices to protect the rights and freedoms of data subjects.

The regulation provides critical legal definitions for personal data, non-personal data, and profiling, the latter of which is specifically defined in Article 4, point (4). It establishes a framework for identifying high risks to the rights and freedoms of data subjects and specifies conditions for using data within AI regulatory sandboxes. Additionally, under this regulation, supervisory authorities may be designated as market surveillance authorities.

Regulation (EU) 2016/679 places particular emphasis on sensitive attributes and characteristics. Article 9(1) protects these sensitive attributes and generally prohibits the processing of biometric data for purposes other than law enforcement, subject to limited exceptions. The regulation further details the legal requirements for processing personal data through specific provisions, including Article 6(4), 9(2), and 22(2)."}
{"entity": "Personal Data", "type": "data", "description": "Personal data refers to any information relating to an identified or identifiable natural person, also known as a data subject. Identification may occur through direct identifiers such as names and ID numbers, or through location data and specific physical, genetic, mental, economic, cultural, or social identity factors. This comprehensive category includes general information as well as sensitive or special categories, such as racial or ethnic origin, biometric data, genetic data, health data, data of children, and information concerning criminal convictions and offenses.

The processing of personal data—which encompasses collection, use, consultation, storage, disclosure, and transmission—is strictly governed by legal frameworks, most notably Regulation (EU) 2016/679. It is managed by controllers and processors who must adhere to principles of lawfulness, fairness, transparency, security, and data minimization. These entities are required to implement technical and organizational protection measures to ensure confidentiality and prevent unlawful use or disclosure. Data subjects maintain specific rights over their information, including the rights to rectification, restriction, erasure, and processing limitations.

Personal data is handled by various entities, including private companies and public authorities, for diverse purposes such as archiving, statistical analysis, and scientific or historical research. In the field of artificial intelligence, personal data processed during the design, development, or use of AI systems requires rigorous documentation regarding its original collection purpose. While data collected for other purposes may be processed for public interest goals within AI regulatory sandboxes or real-world testing, information gathered during testing phases must be strictly protected and deleted upon request or project completion.

Furthermore, the movement of personal data is subject to stringent regulations, particularly when transferred between the Union, third countries, and international organizations. Such transfers are regulated to ensure that protection and legality conditions are maintained across borders. In legal contexts, personal data also serves as the focal point for identifying infringements during processing operations."}
