{"entity": "Regulation (EU) 2023/2854", "type": "content", "description": "A European Union regulation concerning the transfer of non-personal data.<SEP>Also known as the Data Act, this regulation establishes harmonised rules on fair access to and use of data."}
{"entity": "Data Subjects", "type": "person", "description": "Data subjects are natural persons whose personal data is processed. These individuals are the primary focus of data protection frameworks, as the processing of their information can place their fundamental rights and freedoms at risk.

Under Union law and specific regulations, data subjects possess a variety of legally enforceable rights and guarantees. These include specific protections regarding the processing of their data, as well as rights related to profiling and automated individual decision-making.

Furthermore, the status of data subjects plays a critical role in regulatory oversight. Their interests are protected through the implementation of urgency procedures by supervisory authorities, and the impact on these individuals may determine the competence of a supervisory authority in specific legal cases."}
{"entity": "Regulation (EC) No 45/2001", "type": "artifact", "description": "A regulation of the European Parliament and of the Council concerning the protection of individuals with regard to the processing of personal data by Community institutions and bodies.<SEP>A specific regulation applying to the processing of personal data by Union institutions, bodies, offices, and agencies.<SEP>A regulation that applies to the processing of personal data by Union institutions, bodies, offices, and agencies."}
{"entity": "Regulation (EU) 2018/1725", "type": "content", "description": "Regulation (EU) 2018/1725 is a European Union regulation enacted by the European Parliament and the Council to safeguard the fundamental right to the protection of personal data. It specifically governs the protection of natural persons with regard to the processing of personal data by Union institutions, bodies, offices, and agencies. This legal act ensures that data protection standards are upheld within the EU's own administrative framework, including governing the Commission's role as the controller of the EU database and applicable data protection requirements for the use of personal data within AI regulatory sandboxes.

The regulation provides critical legal definitions and constraints for data processing. Specifically, Article 3, point (5) provides the definition for profiling, and the regulation also establishes a formal definition for biometric data. Regarding the usage of such sensitive information, Article 10(1) prohibits the processing of biometric data for purposes other than law enforcement, subject to limited exceptions.

Furthermore, Regulation (EU) 2018/1725 serves as a key legal reference for identifying high risks to the rights and freedoms of data subjects, ensuring a comprehensive framework for privacy and accountability across all Union bodies."}
{"entity": "Personal Data Protection Legislation", "type": "content", "description": "Legislation focused on the protection of personal data, the enforcement of which is facilitated through international cooperation and mutual assistance."}
{"entity": "Special Categories Of Personal Data", "type": "data", "description": "Special categories of personal data are specific types of personal data referred to in Regulation (EU) 2016/679, Directive (EU) 2016/680, and Regulation (EU) 2018/1725.<SEP>Sensitive personal information that may be exceptionally processed for bias detection and correction under strict safeguards.<SEP>Special categories of personal data include genetic data, biometric data, and data concerning health, which merit higher protection.<SEP>Sensitive personal information that may be processed for reasons of public interest, such as public health, without the subject's consent, provided specific protective measures are in place.<SEP>Sensitive personal data, such as racial or ethnic origin, political opinions, religion, or health status, which requires stricter conditions for automated processing.<SEP>Sensitive personal data revealing racial or ethnic origin, political opinions, religious or philosophical beliefs, trade union membership, genetic data, biometric data, health data, or data concerning sex life or sexual orientation."}
{"entity": "AI Systems", "type": "artifact", "description": "AI Systems are a fast-evolving family of software and technological tools based on artificial intelligence, encompassing a broad range of technologies including those integrating general-purpose AI models. These systems serve as tools to assist people, public authorities, and judicial authorities, and may function as components of larger IT systems or be provided as intermediary services. Their applications are diverse, spanning workforce management, recruitment, benefit determination, credit scoring, risk assessment, and the safeguarding of substantial public interests in sectors such as energy, transport, public health, and the environment.

Many AI Systems are capable of complex functions such as profiling, risk analytics, evaluation, and the classification of natural persons. This includes sensitive capabilities such as facial recognition, emotion detection or inference, and remote biometric identification and categorization. Some systems may be utilized for more controversial purposes, including social scoring, manipulative practices, or influencing democratic processes.

Due to their potential impact, AI Systems are categorized by risk levels, specifically distinguished as high-risk or non-high-risk. High-risk systems are those that significantly impact fundamental rights, health, or safety. Consequently, these technologies are subject to harmonized rules for market placement and use, including strict requirements for cybersecurity, accessibility, quality management, and the provision of technical documentation. They are also subject to enforcement, monitoring, and obligations regarding the detection and disclosure of artificially generated or manipulated outputs.

The development and deployment of AI Systems must adhere to principles of safety, transparency, and ethics, guided by clear objectives and key performance indicators. Developers are encouraged to minimize environmental impacts and avoid negative effects on vulnerable persons. To foster innovation, particularly for SMEs and start-ups, certain systems may be developed and tested within AI regulatory sandboxes. In practice, these systems may be supervised, put into service, used by Union institutions, or subjected to rigorous testing in real-world conditions to balance economic and societal benefits with the protection of public interests and fundamental rights."}
{"entity": "Data Protection By Default", "type": "concept", "description": "Data protection by default is a principle ensuring that only necessary personal data is processed by default.</entity>"}
{"entity": "Deployer", "type": "organization", "description": "A Deployer is any natural or legal person, including public authorities, agencies, bodies, or Union institutions, who uses an AI system under their authority for professional, regulatory, or specific purposes. This definition explicitly excludes those who use AI systems for personal, non-professional activities. A Deployer is the entity to whom AI systems, user interfaces, and instructions for use are made available.

In the context of high-risk AI systems, a Deployer is the entity that puts the system into service and uses it to make decisions. They are responsible for the system's proper operation, monitoring, and adherence to the provided instructions for use to ensure the system operates as intended. This includes implementing necessary technical and organizational measures, maintaining documentation, and interpreting system outputs through proper oversight. Deployers must be aware of potential risks outlined in the instructions for use and are obligated to provide explanations for decisions made based on the system's output.

Furthermore, Deployers of high-risk AI systems bear significant regulatory and ethical responsibilities. These include performing fundamental rights impact assessments, identifying risks, and notifying market surveillance authorities. When acting as or on behalf of a public authority, they must register the use of high-risk AI systems in the EU database. They are also tasked with informing affected natural persons about the system's operation and disclosing when content has been artificially generated or manipulated.

Legally, Deployers are subject to specific regulations when established within the Union or when the system's output is intended for use in the Union, making them liable for infringements in Member States. While primarily a user, a Deployer may be considered a provider of a high-risk AI system under certain conditions, such as when they modify the system significantly. Additionally, a Deployer may be a prospective entity that cooperates with providers to conduct testing in real-world conditions. In many instances, the Deployer may hold a power imbalance over the persons affected by the AI system's deployment."}
{"entity": "Fundamental Rights and Freedoms", "type": "concept", "description": "The essential rights and freedoms of individuals that the Regulation aims to protect and that third countries must safeguard in cooperation frameworks.<SEP>The inherent rights of natural persons that must be protected during the processing and transfer of personal data."}
{"entity": "Article 17", "type": "content", "description": "A specific regulatory article defining the requirements for the quality management system.<SEP>A legal provision concerning the erasure of personal data, also referred to as the right to be forgotten."}
{"entity": "Union Law", "type": "concept", "description": "Union law is the overarching legal framework of the European Union, comprising a comprehensive body of laws including regulations, the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU), and the Charter of Fundamental Rights. It is designed to protect public and individual interests, fundamental rights, and ensure principles of non-discrimination, due process, and judicial remedy. This body of law applies throughout the European Union and provides the general principles for procedural safeguards and the exercise of supervisory authority powers.

A primary focus of Union law is the regulation of data processing and the protection of personal data. It establishes the conditions, safeguards, and legal bases for processing tasks in the public interest, specifying the purposes and means of processing and the criteria for nominating a controller. It governs the disclosure of information, including the public disclosure of data held by public authorities, and manages professional secrecy and confidentiality obligations. Furthermore, Union law provides the framework for derogating from the prohibition of processing special categories of personal data, authorizes automated decision-making, and may impose restrictions on data rights. It also regulates data transfers to third countries and governs the binding contracts and legal acts between controllers and processors.

Beyond data protection, Union law spans diverse domains including consumer protection, competition law, copyright, intellectual property, and legal metrology. It specifically governs law enforcement, migration, border control, and the acquisition and use of biometric data. In the realm of emerging technology, it regulates the market placement and operation of AI systems, the use of AI regulatory sandboxes, and AI applications for fraud detection and capital requirement calculations in financial services. Additionally, it establishes requirements for risk management and evaluation practices. While providing a unified structure, Union law allows Member States to introduce more restrictive laws in certain instances, though all research activities and related regulations must strictly adhere to this overarching system."}
{"entity": "Directive (EU) 2016/680", "type": "artifact", "description": "Directive (EU) 2016/680 is a European Union directive of the European Parliament and the Council designed to safeguard the fundamental right to the protection of personal data. It specifically governs the processing of personal data by competent authorities, including police and criminal justice authorities, for the purposes of the prevention, investigation, detection, or prosecution of criminal offences.

The directive establishes comprehensive rules for data protection within law enforcement contexts. It provides critical definitions for key concepts, such as profiling, which is defined in Article 3, point (4), and biometric data. Detailed regulations regarding the processing of personal and biometric data are specifically outlined in Article 8 and Article 10. Additionally, the directive addresses the powers of supervisory authorities, including provisions under which they may be designated as market surveillance authorities.

As a binding legal act, Directive (EU) 2016/680 interacts with current Regulations and sets a compliance standard that AI systems must adhere to when processing data for law enforcement purposes.<SEP>A specific Union legal act of the European Parliament and of the Council governing personal data processed by public authorities for the prevention, investigation, detection, or prosecution of criminal offences.<SEP>A directive regarding the protection of natural persons in relation to the processing of personal data by competent authorities for criminal law purposes."}
{"entity": "Right To The Protection Of Personal Data", "type": "concept", "description": "A fundamental right pursuant to the Regulation that must be balanced with freedom of expression.<SEP>A fundamental right established pursuant to the Regulation that must be balanced against freedom of expression and public access to documents.</entity>"}
{"entity": "Artificial Intelligence", "type": "concept", "description": "Artificial Intelligence refers to the technology and systems that are the primary subject of the regulation and ethical frameworks discussed."}
{"entity": "Article 23", "type": "content", "description": "A regulation article detailing restrictions on the obligations and rights of data subjects and controllers."}
{"entity": "AI System", "type": "artifact", "description": "An AI System is a machine-based technological entity designed to infer outputs—such as predictions, content, recommendations, or decisions—by deriving models or algorithms from inputs or data. Operating with varying levels of autonomy and adaptiveness, these systems can consist of integrated components, tools, and services, including AI models and user interfaces, to influence their environments. They are utilized across a broad spectrum of domains, including military, civilian, humanitarian, scientific research, and national security, serving purposes that range from improving human activity and detecting decision-making patterns to performing preparatory tasks.

Specific applications of an AI System include remote biometric identification, biometric verification, biometric categorization, and emotion recognition. Because these systems can generate or manipulate content and profile natural persons, they are often subject to regulatory oversight, including transparency obligations and strict guarantees regarding privacy and personal data protection throughout their lifecycle.

A critical distinction is made between AI systems based on their risk level. An AI System may be classified as high-risk if its intended purpose or use case poses a potential threat to health, safety, the environment, or fundamental rights. Such high-risk systems are subject to rigorous regulatory compliance, including conformity assessments, the maintenance of technical documentation, the use of quality training data, and monitoring of performance, capabilities, and limitations.

Depending on their classification and the gravity of any infringements, an AI System may be required to undergo substantial modification, recall, or withdrawal from the market. Whether categorized as general-purpose or high-risk, these systems are characterized by their trade name, intended purpose, and operating logic, and must meet essential requirements to be legally placed on the market or put into service."}
{"entity": "This Regulation", "type": "artifact", "description": "Based on the provided descriptions, there appear to be two distinct legal frameworks referred to as "This Regulation."

The first is a comprehensive regulatory framework for Artificial Intelligence, adopted on the basis of Article 16 TFEU. This legislative act governs the use of AI systems and the processing of biometric data, particularly within the context of law enforcement. It establishes a governance framework for implementation and enforcement, setting specific obligations for providers, deployers, and notified bodies. Key requirements under this framework include standards for data governance, cybersecurity, and conformity assessments for high-risk AI systems. Additionally, it provides essential definitions for key roles and terms and outlines specific exclusions, such as those for personal non-professional use and certain licensing conditions.

The second is a legal act focused on data protection, designed to protect natural persons regarding the processing of personal data and to ensure the free movement of such data within the Union. This regulation provides a comprehensive framework for data protection, transparency, and the transfer of personal data to third countries and international organizations. It specifies the conditions for the lawfulness of personal data processing, establishing a general framework that does not require a separate specific law for every individual processing operation."}
{"entity": "Data Subject", "type": "person", "description": "A Data Subject is an identified or identifiable natural person to whom personal data relates and whose data is being processed. This individual may include children and is the central figure whose fundamental rights, freedoms, and human dignity must be safeguarded throughout the data processing lifecycle.

The Data Subject possesses a comprehensive suite of enforceable rights under the Regulation, including the rights of access, rectification, erasure (the right to be forgotten), restriction of processing, and data portability. They hold the authority to object to processing, monitor how their data is handled, and exercise specific rights regarding profiling and automated decision-making. Furthermore, the Data Subject has the right to be informed about the processing of their data, including the extent to which consent is given, and retains the power to provide, withdraw, or give explicit consent.

To ensure protection and accountability, the Data Subject is entitled to various safeguards and legal remedies. They have the right to lodge complaints with a supervisory authority, contact a Data Protection Officer, and seek legal redress or full and effective compensation for damages suffered. In the event of a high-risk data breach, the Data Subject must be notified. Additionally, their rights and freedoms are considered during data protection impact assessments, and they may be consulted during the creation of codes of conduct. Member States must also consider the specific rights of the Data Subject when adopting any exemptions to these protections."}
{"entity": "Natural Persons", "type": "person", "description": "Natural Persons are human beings who possess fundamental rights and freedoms, including the right to the protection of their personal data. In the context of data processing, Natural Persons are individuals whose personal data is processed, necessitating transparency in such operations. While they are the primary beneficiaries of data protection ensured by the Regulation, they are also individuals whose rights and freedoms may be subjected to risks resulting from these data processing operations. Consequently, they are granted the authority to report infringements of the Regulation to safeguard their interests.

In the specific context of AI systems, Natural Persons interact with, are overseen by, or are subject to AI operations. They may function as active participants who define software rules, as qualified personnel with the competence and authority to verify identifications and evaluate results, or as supervisors who monitor high-risk AI systems to detect anomalies.

As subjects of AI applications—particularly within law enforcement, public services, employment, and education—Natural Persons may undergo emotion recognition, identification, biometric categorization, risk assessment, classification, and evaluation. Those within the Union are specifically protected against AI-predicted behavior and biometric emotion detection.

To protect their health, safety, and fundamental rights from the risks associated with high-risk AI systems, Natural Persons are entitled to specific protections. These include the right to be informed when they are interacting with an AI system, when their biometric data is being processed, or when they are subject to high-risk AI systems. Additionally, they have the right to receive explanations regarding the outcomes produced by such systems."}
