{"entity": "Directive (EU) 2016/680", "type": "artifact", "description": "Directive (EU) 2016/680 is a European Union directive of the European Parliament and the Council designed to safeguard the fundamental right to the protection of personal data. It specifically governs the processing of personal data by competent authorities, including police and criminal justice authorities, for the purposes of the prevention, investigation, detection, or prosecution of criminal offences.

The directive establishes comprehensive rules for data protection within law enforcement contexts. It provides critical definitions for key concepts, such as profiling, which is defined in Article 3, point (4), and biometric data. Detailed regulations regarding the processing of personal and biometric data are specifically outlined in Article 8 and Article 10. Additionally, the directive addresses the powers of supervisory authorities, including provisions under which they may be designated as market surveillance authorities.

As a binding legal act, Directive (EU) 2016/680 interacts with current Regulations and sets a compliance standard that AI systems must adhere to when processing data for law enforcement purposes.<SEP>A specific Union legal act of the European Parliament and of the Council governing personal data processed by public authorities for the prevention, investigation, detection, or prosecution of criminal offences.<SEP>A directive regarding the protection of natural persons in relation to the processing of personal data by competent authorities for criminal law purposes."}
